parameters: <WordWrap>Add passive states to your game! They can be innate to actors, classes, appear when a piece of equipment is worn, or after an actor learns a skill! Having a passive state increase gameplay depth by a lot!

<WordWrap>Passive states are states that are automatically active. You can think of them as an extension of traits but with more flexibility. They will always be there as long as the actor or enemy has auto passive state notetags.

<WordWrap>This plugin allows enemies to function off of a leveling system. An enemy's level will be increased relative to the player under specific rulings and will increase its stats based on its level.
<WordWrap>When an enemy is made in battle, it will create its initial level off of a set of rules. These are the various rules you can change the ‘Default Type’ plugin parameter to reflect.
<WordWrap>Type 0 – Lowest level of all actors that have joined the player party.
<WordWrap>Type 1 – Lowest level of all actors that are in the battling party.
<WordWrap>Type 2 – Average level of all actors that have joined the player party.
<WordWrap>Type 3 – Average level of all actors that are in the battling party.
<WordWrap>Type 4 – Highest level of all actors that have joined the player party.
<WordWrap>Type 5 – Highest level of all actors that are in the battling party.
<WordWrap>After the level type has been determined for the enemy, random level fluctuations are then added.

<WordWrap>The \TP system in \c[4]RPG Maker MV\c[0] is rather limiting. A lot of the TP system is hardcoded in giving RPG Maker MV users very little control over how much \TP gain a battler can receive from particular actions and situations.

<WordWrap>This plugin gives you the ability to adjust how much \TP battlers will acquire from various actions, different \TP modes, and letting players select and pick what \TP mode they want for each actor.
<WordWrap>\TP Modes are given to your actors for them to decide how they want to gain \TP over the course of battle. You can decide the rulings for each \TP Mode.
<WordWrap>Here is an overview of what each \TP Mode Parameter does:
– This is the name of the \TP Mode. This is what appears in the \TP Mode selection menu in the \c[4]Skill Menu\c[0] (if you have it enabled).
– This is the icon used for the \TP Mode in the \TP Mode selection menu in the \c[4]Skill Menu\c[0] (if you have it enabled).
– This is the help description used for the \TP Mode in the \TP Mode selection menu in the \c[4]Skill Menu\c[0] (if you have it enabled).
– If set to true, then the user carries any earned \TP from on battle to the next battle. If set to false, the at the start and each of each battle the user’s \TP value is cleared.
– This is the formula to determine how much \TP is gained at the start of battle. Previously, this was reserved for non-preserved \TP values. Now, it can be used regardless.
– This is how much \TP is regenerated during the regeneration phase for the user. Typically, the regeneration phase occurs at the end of each turn.
– This is how much \TP is generated from the user taking \HP damage. The amount of damage taken can be retrieved from the ‘value’ variable.
– This is how much \TP is generated from the user dealing \HP damage. The amount of damage taken can be retrieved from the ‘value’ variable.
– This is how much \TP is generated from the user healing \HP damage. The amount of damage taken can be retrieved from the ‘value’ variable.
– This is how much \TP is generated from an ally taking \HP damage. The amount of damage taken can be retrieved from the ‘value’ variable.
– This is how much \TP is generated from the user taking \MP damage. The amount of damage taken can be retrieved from the ‘value’ variable.
– This is how much \TP is generated from the user dealing \MP damage. The amount of damage taken can be retrieved from the ‘value’ variable.
– This is how much \TP is generated from the user healing \MP damage. The amount of damage taken can be retrieved from the ‘value’ variable.
– This is how much \TP is generated from an ally taking \MP damage. The amount of damage taken can be retrieved from the ‘value’ variable.
– This is how much \TP is generated from the user issuing a state on a foe. If the user and target are on the same team, ignore this.
– This is how much \TP is generated from the user gaining a state from a foe. If the user and origin are on the same team, ignore this.
– This is how much \TP is generated if an allied member dies. It does not matter who the killer is.
– This is how much \TP is generated if an enemy member dies. It does not matter who the killer is.
– This is how much \TP is generated from the player winning a battle.
– This is how much \TP is generated from the player escaping a battle.
– This is how much \TP is generated from the player losing a battle.
– This is how much \TP is generated during the Regen \TP timing if the user is in a critical \HP state.
– This is how much \TP is generated during the Regen \TP timing if the user is in a critical \MP state.
– This is how much \TP is generated during the Regen \TP timing if the user is the only alive member left.
– This is how much \TP is generated whenever the user manages to evade an action performed by another battler.
<WordWrap>And that's it for the list of parameters you can use per \TP Mode!
<WordWrap>In case 20 \TP Modes aren't enough, you can extend the amount up to 100 through the \c[4]More TP Modes\c[0] extension plugins.
\>What \c[4]Equip Battle Skills Plugins\c[0] would you like to learn about?\<
<WordWrap>This plugin creates a new gameplay mechanic where players have to choose which skills to bring into battle.
<WordWrap>They can select what skills to bring from the skill menu. In addition to being able to do that, equipped skills can also add bonuses such as stats and/or passive states.
<WordWrap>For those who are using the \c[4]Equip Battle Skills\c[0] plugin, you may have noticed that the '\c[4]Skills\c[0]' command replaces all skill types in the battle command window.
<WordWrap>For those who'd like to have certain skill types continue working, you can use this plugin to create an exception for it.
<WordWrap>The skill types found listed in the plugin parameters will be given an exception and will be shown in battle.
<WordWrap>Any skill that contains the skill type also cannot be equipped in a battle skill slot.

<WordWrap>This plugin imposes a limit upon actors to limit what skills can be equipped based on tiers. The player must abide by the limits before being able to exit the menu allowing for better control over gameplay balance.

<WordWrap>This plugin by itself will not change any major game functions, but instead, it works in combination with other plugins that make use of this plugin’s functions should you decide to incorporate \c[4]Job Points\c[0] into your game.

<WordWrap>When \c[4]Job Points\c[0] are earned, they are given to the actor’s current class. If the actor were to switch classes, then the Job Points will be changed to that class’s \c[4]Job Points\c[0] until reverted back.
\>What \c[4]Party System Plugins\c[0] would you like to learn about?\<
<WordWrap>This plugin replaces the “\c[4]Formation\c[0]” command found in the in-game menu with a new scene where the player can adjust the party he or she wants in a more comfortable way.
<WordWrap>Games using the \c[4]Battle Engine Core\c[0] will also gain the ability to switch party midway through battle.

<WordWrap>For games that benefit more from individual party switching, this plugin grants players the ability to switch party members on an individual basis rather than entire parties at a time mid-battle.
<WordWrap>However, actors that have just switched in and are on cooldown, required for battle, or locked in the party position cannot switch out.
<WordWrap>This plugin places party members into row formations to give them distinct advantages based on row location in the form of states for maximum control.
<WordWrap>Skills and items are capable of moving targets to different row locations.

<WordWrap>So what are rows, you ask? Rows are positions your party members are placed in. Depending on how you set up the rows for your project, rows can provide different advantages to the party members for just simply being in that row.
<WordWrap>These advantages are granted through the states that are given to the party members from the plugin parameter settings. How you set up these advantages is entirely up to you.
<WordWrap>Here is an example of a row setup:
Members in the front row will receive full damage from the Melee element.
Members in the middle row will receive slightly less damage from the Melee element, but the Attack command is sealed unless they have a ranged weapon.
Members in the back row will receive a lot less damage fom the Melee element and also cannot use the Attack command unless equipped with a ranged weapon.
<WordWrap>How you choose to set up your rows is dependent on how you can set up your states that affect those rows. These states cannot be removed by skills and are considered a passive effect.
<WordWrap>Stealing is a commonly used mechanic found in many traditional RPG's. This plugin enables you to replicate that mechanic and add more depth upon it.

<WordWrap>Enemies can have multiple items to steal in addition to their default drops. When an actor goes to steal from an enemy, the actor has a percent change for the steal attempt to be successful.
<WordWrap>If successful, the actor grabs a random item from the stealable items pool and the party gains the said item.

<WordWrap>In addition to stealing, there is a new mechanic called ‘Snatch’. While stealing allows your actors to grab random items from the enemy, snatching lets your actors target the item they want to steal and focus only on that item alone.

<WordWrap>Another feature for this plugin is that stealing a piece of equipment can now ‘debuff’ the enemy. If an actor steals a sword that gives 10 ATK, the enemy will lose 10 ATK. This feature can be turned off.

<WordWrap>Also new (and optional) is the ability to steal the enemy’s drop items. Enemies won’t always necessarily drop their items after being defeated, but stealing from them directly will allow your players to secure those items.
<WordWrap>Once an item is stolen, it will not drop again at the end of battle.
